The paper deals with the design and implementation of a matching market for the Israeli Mechinot gap-year programs, which involves a rich set of diversity considerations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms for strategic interactions. Additionally, the paper involves the development of a preference-specification language and corresponding choice-function semantics, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which deals with the development of intelligent agents and decision-making algorithms. The paper also involves the use of data structures and algorithms for efficient matching, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of the theoretical properties of the preference-specification language and choice-function semantics, which suggests that it may also belong to the Learning (cs.LG) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories, which deal with the analysis of machine learning algorithms and social networks, respectively.
